{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636179"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:24:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:24:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17569"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17569"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10259"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112016"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10259"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17569"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94082"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10054"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45881"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112016"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECells interconvert energy and matter through paired metabolic pathways. Energy currency and redox cofactors link these pathways to cellular demands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA biochemistry practical asks you to identify the characteristic energetic and redox features that distinguish the two major classes of metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the energy and redox coupling of metabolic pathways?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Catabolism uses ATP and NADPH; anabolism produces ATP and NADH","Catabolism produces ATP and NADPH; anabolism uses ATP and NADH","Catabolism uses ATP and NADH; anabolism produces ATP and NADPH","Catabolism produces ATP and NADH; anabolism uses ATP and NADPH","Both pathways primarily use NADPH for redox reactions"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatabolism produces ATP and NADH; anabolism uses ATP and NADPH\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the metabolic coupling. Catabolic pathways break down fuels, releasing energy captured as ATP and reducing power as NADH and FADH2. Anabolic pathways consume ATP for biosynthesis and use NADPH as the reducing agent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatabolism uses ATP and NADPH; anabolism produces ATP and NADH\u003C/strong\u003E reverses the actual roles of these pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatabolism produces ATP and NADPH; anabolism uses ATP and NADH\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly assigns NADPH production to catabolism and NADH use to anabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatabolism uses ATP and NADH; anabolism produces ATP and NADPH\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly suggests that biosynthetic pathways generate energy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth pathways primarily use NADPH for redox reactions\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as catabolism primarily generates NADH and FADH2 for the electron transport chain, while anabolism uses NADPH for reductive biosynthesis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Catabolism releases energy as ATP and produces NADH and FADH2 through fuel oxidation.","Anabolism uses ATP for energy and NADPH as the primary reducing agent for biosynthesis.","The distinct cofactor usage allows cells to regulate catabolic and anabolic pathways independently."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, et al. Principles of anatomy and physiology. 2nd Asia-Pacific ed. Hoboken (NJ): John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2019. Chapter 2, The chemical level of organisation."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94082"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17569"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94082"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-23T20:40:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-23T20:40:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10259"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112016"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-